DocumentRange, EventTarget, ObjectLike
public class JsHTMLDocument
extends DOM2HTML.HTMLDocument.Prototype

An opaque class representing JavaScript client-side objects of the global JsClient.HTMLDocument class.

Author:
J.J.Liu (Jianjun Liu) at http://www.jscripter.org
JavaScript:
Opaque types can be resolved but no class objects for them can be generated into the target codes. Re-compilers must exit with error on the operations of accessing that kind of class objects. The checkcast operation to the class literal of this interface must be ignored and instanceof to it always true.

referrer

public static final Value.String.Member referrer

An opaque static field defining a member that is named by the field name without a qualifying member and to access the property of the name on an object.

The property, identified by this member, of a JsHTMLDocument object refers to a read-only string specifying the URL of the document that linked to this document, or null if this document was not accessed through a hyper-link. This property allows the client-side access to the HTTP referer header. Note the spelling difference, however: the HTTP header has three r's, and the property has four r's.

URL

public static final Value.String.Member URL

An opaque static field defining a member that is named by the field name without a qualifying member and to access the property of the name on an object.

The property, identified by this member, of a JsHTMLDocument object refers to a read-only string specifying the URL of the document. This value is often the same as the JsLocation.href property of the JsWindow object that contains the document. When URL redirection occurs, however, this property holds the actual URL of the document, and JsLocation.href holds the URL that was requested.

close

public final void close()

Closes a document stream opened with the open() method, forcing any buffered output to be displayed.

This method closes a document stream that was opened with the open() method and forces any buffered output to be displayed. If you use the write(String) or writeln(String) methods to dynamically output a document, you must remember to call this method when it is done to ensure that all your document content is displayed. Once you have called this method, you should not call write(String) or writeln(String) again, as this implicitly calls open() to erase the current document and begin a new one.

Since:
1.0
See Also:
open(), write(String), writeln(String)
JavaScript:
Re-compilers must convert the instance invocation of this method directly into a JavaScript invocation on its current object instance without changing the method name, but expanding variable arguments, if any, into comma-separated values.

open

public final void open()

Opens a stream to which new document contents may be written, erasing any current document content.

This method erases the current HTML document and begins a new one, which may be written to with the write(String) and writeln(String) methods. After calling this method to begin a new document and write(String) or writeln(String) to specify document content, you must always remember to call close() to end the document and force its content to be displayed.

This method should not be called by a script or event handler that is part of the document being overwritten, because the script or handler will itself be overwritten.

Since:
1.0
See Also:
close(), write(String), writeln(String)
JavaScript:
Re-compilers must convert the instance invocation of this method directly into a JavaScript invocation on its current object instance without changing the method name, but expanding variable arguments, if any, into comma-separated values.

write

public final void write(java.lang.String text)

Appends a string of HTML text to an open document.

This method appends the specified HTML text to the document. According to the DOM standard, this method takes a single string argument. According to common practice, however, it may be passed any number of arguments. These arguments are converted to strings and appended, in order, to the document.

The method is normally used in one of two ways. First, it can be invoked on the current document within a <script> tag or within a function that is executed while the document is being parsed. In this case, this method writes its HTML output as if that output appeared literally in the file at the location of the code that invoked the method.

Second, you can use this method to dynamically generate new documents in a window, frame, or iframe other than the one in which the calling script is running. If the target document is open, this method appends to that document. If the document is not open, the method discards the existing document and opens a new empty one to which it appends its arguments.

Once a document is open, this method can append any amount of output to the end of the document. When a new document has been completely generated by this technique, the document must be closed by calling close(). Note that although the call to open() is optional, the call to close() is never optional.

The results of calling this method may not be immediately visible in the target document. This is because a web browser may buffer up text to parse and display in larger chunks. Calling close() is the only way to explicitly force all buffered output to be "flushed" and displayed.

Parameters:
text - The HTML text to be appended to the document.
Since:
1.0
See Also:
write(StringLike), write(Vars), writeln(String), close(), open()
JavaScript:
Re-compilers must convert the instance invocation of this method directly into a JavaScript invocation on its current object instance without changing the method name, but expanding variable arguments, if any, into comma-separated values.

writeln

public final void writeln(java.lang.String text)

Appends a string of HTML text followed by a newline character to an open document.

This method is like write(String), except that it follows the appended text with a newline character, which may be useful when writing the content of a <pre> tag, for example.
